ew Roman'; font-size:11pt">lead officer for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equality), with input from heads of disciplines in Natural Sciences, Sports, and Nursing, Midwifery and Health</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Summary</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">University of Stirling recognises </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and is committed to tackling </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the problem of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">retaining women in STEM disciplines.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Individual institutions are limited in their ability to improve numbers of women in STEM, although they can take a number of actions to improve the career path for women once they reach the institution.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government actio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n is required to address the wider societal issue of women in STEM:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">enhanced incentives for men to share childcare responsibilities, including enhanced paternity pay</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">remove stigma of part-time work</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">affordable and more widely-available</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, high quality,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> childc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">active promotion in society of the importance of STEM subjects, and the role for both men and women in STEM </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">active promotion of STEM in schools: both as a subject to take all the way to 6th year, but also as a potential career for all. It is especial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ly important to target some promotion activity to girls.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">About us</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our vision is t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">o be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cknowledged worldwide as a distinguished University that addresses the social and environmental needs of society through innovative, interdisciplinary research and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">education.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our successes are already </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in international league tables, in RAE 2008, 85% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stirling’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> research </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> rated as internationally </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, with 10% being world-leading. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The University has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">circa </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">12300 students, 8800 undergraduates, 350</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">0 postgraduates, representing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">over </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">100 countries. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The University is committed to making full use of the talent pool available in STEM subjects,  but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">recognises</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> there is an imbalance in numbers of men and women in these subjects. We have therefore signed up</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to the Athena SWAN charter and recently submitted an application for a bronze institutional award. Part of that application is an evidence base on women in STEM at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stirling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and an action plan for the next three years to increase numbers of women in STEM.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We are making this submission because as an institution we can only do so much to tackle the problem of retention of women in STEM. This is a much wider societal problem requiring </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> interventions to tackle at the root. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The University currently employs 1421 staff: 37% (527) academic staff and 63% (894) support staff. The University has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eight</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> academic schools: Applied Social Sciences; Arts and Humanities; Education; Sport; Natural Sciences; Nursing, Midwifery &amp; Health, the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stirling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Management School</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stirling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Graduate School</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">STEM at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Stirling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> comprises three of the schools (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Natural Sciences, Nursing, Midwifery and Health, and some of Sport). This is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">37.5%</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of staff numbers overall</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and approximatel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> 40% of academic s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">taff. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder? </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 13.25pt; padding-left:8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In 2012 the University of Stirling collated data on gender balance at different career stages for STEM disciplines. While the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">male:female</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> balance for STEM subje</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cts overall is 45%:55%, this is somewhat skewed for us by the presence of Nursing, Midwifery and Health (balance 77%:23%). Dramatically, we see a fall in female staff as we look from the level of postgraduate researchers through lecturer and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">senior lecture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r to professor grade (number of females falling from 68% through 52% and 40% to 19%). This is a rather typical profile in higher education institutions in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the Equality Challenge Unit Statistical Report 2011 shows 19% at professorial level overall a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nd 44% for non-professorial academic staff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Again, the position in Nursing, Midwifery and Health is a bit more positive, with 50% females in grade 10 posts.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We do not have concrete answers to this problem, but a number of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> possible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> reasons. These relate to actions we have committed to in the next three years to try to improve the balance.</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are not in promoted posts because they do not come forward for promotion. Our figures show that a smaller proportion of the female populatio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n eligible for promotion come forward than the male population. For example, 18%:23% applying for promotion to senior lecturer level, 5%:33% for promotion to senior teaching fellow. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are more likely to stay on lower status fixed-term contract researc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">h posts (60%:40% across STEM at Stirling).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are more likely to have breaks in service (most obviously, maternity leave).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are more likely to work part-time (73% of those on part-time open-ended contracts are female). Moreover, the increasingly lo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ng-hours culture of academia is off-putting to women, who often have additional demands on their time (usually caring responsibilities).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There may be unconscious bias in the system, meaning that women are less likely to receive the support of their manager</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s to progress, and/or are less likely to be selected for promotion (or indeed for activities that could strengthen their case for future promotion).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We don't have any data on this; however, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he consequences </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are clearly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">detrimental</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. For example, economic: w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e have spent money training these people and they have not stayed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in the discipline. See the Tapping All Our Talents report from the Royal Society of Edinburgh for an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> economic analysis for Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There may be benefits (scientifically trained people in other fields bring a different viewpoint, and will help to promote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> wider unders</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tanding of science in society).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Female representation on decision-making bodies </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is both a symptom and perhaps a cause.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> If there are fewer women at senior levels, then they will be less likely to be represented on important committees at that level. But what image does this promote to junior staff, external stakeholders,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> prospectiv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e students?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Universitie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s should lead by example:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> increasing the number of women on such committees to levels closer to the institutional gender balance where possible. These women can then help to influence the decision making process, challenge instituti</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">onal norms that place further barriers in the way of progress for women, and bring fresh perspectives to discussions. Greater representation on senior level committees also provides more visible role models for junior staff. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e note that the need to increa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">se female representation on governance committees can also have the unintended consequence of further burdening talented female staff with administrative activities (the same women are asked again and again to fill certain roles which require a ‘token fema</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">le’) whilst their male counterparts are free to pursue activities that are perhaps more highly valued by senior managers (e.g. academic research; project management; external networking and influencing). Universities need to manage these conflicting issues</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> carefully, perhaps by more visibly valuing the types of activities that women become involved in. Only when there is a more equal balance of males/females at senior levels will the ‘governance burden’ become less of an issue for the small pool of existing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> senior women. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">At Stirling we are planning to run </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a series of training events. There are two </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">kinds proposed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. On one hand, we wish to offer training to women to be more confident and assertive in progressing their career. On the other, it is important that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> improving the gender balance is not just the responsibility o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f women in an institution,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> therefore we will also require unconscious bias training for senior staff and decision-making bodies such as appointment c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ommittees and promotion panels.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We are also p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">romoting a mentoring scheme for staff, to provide on-to-one encouragement and advice. We are keen to ensure that all women taking part in our development training will also receive the ongoing support of a senior mentor.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Maternity leave and childcare issue</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s remain significant. We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are exploring the feasibility</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of mechanisms</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to support the reintegration of those returning from maternity leave</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a phased return to teaching to enable returners to focus more intensively on research activity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, or provision </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of additional research support, such as a studentship</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Part-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">time working is still </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">not widely accepted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in many institutions, or within certain departments within institutions. The lack of part-time posts (or flexible working arrangeme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nts) at senior levels p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">resents </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a challenge to talented women who wish to combine raising a family with career development and progression. W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">omen are afraid to adopt a part-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">time arrangement lest they lose credibility as a professional, miss out on progression/development opportunities, or have to risk permanently losing the opportunity to work full time in the future. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Institutions need to understand and visibly espouse the v</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">alues of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">part-time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> working for men and women (and for the institution) to remove the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">stigma and change the culture. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Flexible working is an important part of this: those with caring responsibilities often have to respond to unexpected crisis situations req</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">uiring their presence at home, at school, at hospital etc. These cannot simply be scheduled into a standard pattern of working.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Scheduling of important meetings, seminars and so on must take account of flexible working patterns. Meetings should be kept to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">core hours. Efforts should be made to schedule special events so that those working flexibly can attend.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Funding to support additional child-care resources for such events would facilitate attendance.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Other organisations (notably funders, such as the resea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rch councils, and the Chief Scientist's Office) must also be cognisant of the possibility of flexible working in those applying to them for funding. For example, short deadlines (of a few days) are the norm to respond to reviewers' comments, and for some f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">unding applications (of two weeks). This is unreasonably short for part-time workers and, given the higher number of women in part-time roles, disadvantages that group.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The so-called two-body problem is common in academia: in a couple where both are academ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ics, if one moves to a new institution, then their partner may have to take a disadvantageous step in their own career. Often it is a female partner who follows a male partner and therefore has the disadvantage. Institutions could facilitate faculty positi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ons for partners where possible. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Nursing, Midwifery and Health take extra measures to encourage nurses to move from clinical practice into research with tailored academic fellow positions. These are currently all held by women, and are essentially PhD stu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dentships with a higher than normal stipend in return for some teaching duties.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.3pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Institutions can do more to raise the p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rofile of female STEM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> colleagues. At Stirling, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mages chosen to publicise the University are required to portray a diverse University pop</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ulation (Marketing policy: “Where possible the models selected should be a cross section of the student body including male, female and international students.”). Many of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> website and prospectus images obviously of scientists (e.g. in a lab, with test </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ubes, microscopes) show women.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers? </span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Encouraging institutions to offer extended paternity leave remunerated at the same levels of pay that women on maternity l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eave would receive.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Removal of stigma of part-time work. Encourage/incentivise institutions to think creatively about policies supporting </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">part-time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and flexible working.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Affordable and more widely-available</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, high quality,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> childcare provision (including out of school hours provision) which working parents could easily access</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (i.e. is conveniently located to the workplace)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Promotion in society of the importance of STEM subjects, and the abilities of both men and women to carry out such roles.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> For example, a public awareness-raising campaign profiling female scientists, engineers, technologists, and medical professionals.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hildren and their parents need to be aware from a very early stage (birth!) that STEM careers are open for boys and girls. What more could the government do to work with nursery schools, childcare providers and primary schools? Also, careers professionals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in high schools need to be much more active in promoting science disciplines as potential careers for girls. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 11pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Work with schools to ensure that pupils are able to take a wide range of science subjects all the way until 6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> year. Anecdotal evidence from Scot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">land suggests that some schools have introduced curricula that prevent pupils from taking all three sciences. This must be addressed, not only in the interests of increasing the number of women in SET careers, but to ensure that Scottish pupils retain pari</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ty with those studying in schools south of the border. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The government could give consideration to providing additional funding to institutions to support outreach activities designed to promote careers in science for women and girls. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Declaration of int</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">erests</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 18.75pt; padding-left:2.55pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our interest as a UK HEI is that by improving the situation with regard to the careers of women in STEM we would increase the talent available at all levels of the institution, and show that STEM subjects are viable career options for younger women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(coming in at undergraduate level).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Tapping all our Talents: Women in Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics: A Strategy for Scotland, Royal Society of Edinburgh 2012. ISBN 0902198661, 9780902198661.</sp